<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="414" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,151,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[504,743,153,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="guianensis">
<emphasis box="[504,743,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Dracaena guianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Amazonia, distributed along the Amazon River and some of its main tributaries, and the coastal area in 
<collectingCountry box="[777,845,188,213]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[861,929,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,991,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,983,1894]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of examined material of Cnemidophorus lemniscatus, Cnemidophorus sp. 2, Cnemidophorus sp. 3, and Dracaena guianensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/197983/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). We examined material from 
<collectingCountry box="[1271,1366,188,213]" name="Ecuador" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1378,1432,189,212]" name="Peru" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[199,267,223,248]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(states of 
<collectingRegion box="[386,470,224,248]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Amapá</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[481,534,224,248]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Pará</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[594,714,224,248]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[738,807,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,991,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,983,1894]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of examined material of Cnemidophorus lemniscatus, Cnemidophorus sp. 2, Cnemidophorus sp. 3, and Dracaena guianensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/197983/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), but it also occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[1060,1229,223,248]" name="French Guiana" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
<collectingRegion box="[1060,1229,223,248]" country="France" name="Guyane" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">French Guiana</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1241,1354,223,248]" name="Colombia" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, and in 
<collectingRegion box="[151,265,260,285]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Maranhão</collectingRegion>
state, in 
<collectingCountry box="[371,439,260,285]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Daudin" box="[456,609,260,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Daudin, F. M. (1802) Histoire naturelle, generalle et particulieres des reptiles. Tome III. F. Dufart, Paris, 452 pp." type="book" year="1802">Daudin 1802</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ayala" box="[622,754,260,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Ayala, S. C. (1986) Saurios de Colombia: lista actualizada, y distribucion de ejemplares colombianos en los museos. Caldasia, 15, 555 - 575." type="journal article" year="1986">Ayala 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini" box="[767,1078,260,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; Valencia, J. (1966) The genus Dracaena, with a brief consideration of macroteiid relationships (Sauria, Teiidae). Arquivos de Zoologia, 13, 7 - 35." type="journal article" year="1966">Vanzolini &amp; Valencia 1966</bibRefCitation>
, respectively). Despite its wide distribution, there are few records of 
<taxonomicName box="[590,748,297,320]" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="guianensis">
<emphasis box="[590,748,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">D. guianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the wild in collections and in scientific literature (in contrast to 
<collectionCode box="[275,353,332,356]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">CITES</collectionCode>
trade records, especially in the 1980’s—http://www.cites.org/eng/resources/quotas/index.shtml). It is semiaquatic and diurnal, inhabits seasonally flooded lowlands, swamps, small streams and lakes, where it is found in the water, on the ground near water, and on branches of low trees emerging from water (
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini" box="[1255,1431,404,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. (1961) Notas bionomicas sobre Dracaena guianensis no Para (Sauria, Teiidae). Papeis Avulsos do Departamento de Zoologia, Secretaria de Agricultura, 14, 237 - 241." type="journal article" year="1961">Vanzolini 1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini" box="[151,463,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; Valencia, J. (1966) The genus Dracaena, with a brief consideration of macroteiid relationships (Sauria, Teiidae). Arquivos de Zoologia, 13, 7 - 35." type="journal article" year="1966">Vanzolini &amp; Valencia 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Crump" box="[477,623,440,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Crump, M. L. (1971) Quantitative analysis of the ecological distribution of a tropical herpetofauna. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Natural History, the University of Kansas, 3, 1 - 62." type="journal article" year="1971">Crump 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[637,875,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Dixon, J. R. &amp; Soini, P. (1975) The reptiles of the upper Amazon Basin, Iquitos region, Peru. Part 1. Lizards and Amphisbaenians. Milwaukee Public Museum, Contributions in Biology and Geology, 4, 1 - 58." type="journal article" year="1975">Dixon &amp; Soini 1975</bibRefCitation>
, 1986; 
<bibRefCitation author="Duellman" box="[961,1140,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Duellman, W. E. (1978) The biology of an Equatorial Herpetofauna in Amazonian Ecuador. Miscellaneous Publications, Museum of Natural History of University of Kansas, 65, 1 - 352." type="journal article" year="1978">Duellman 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Duellman" box="[1154,1432,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Duellman, W. E. &amp; Salas, A. W. (1991) Annotated checklist of the amphibians and reptiles of Cuzco Amazonico, Peru. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Natural History, the University of Kansas, 143, 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="1991">Duellman &amp; Salas 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila-Pires" box="[151,348,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Avila-Pires, T. C. S. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">Ávila-Pires 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mesquita" box="[363,620,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Mesquita, D. O., Colli, G. R., Costa, G. C., Franca, F. G. R., Garda, A. A. &amp; Peres, A. K. Jr. (2006 b) At the Water's Edge: Ecology of Semiaquatic Teiids in Brazilian Amazon. Journal of Herpetology, 40, 221 - 229. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1670 / 123 - 05 A. 1" type="journal article" year="2006" yearSuffix="b">
Mesquita 
<emphasis box="[477,536,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">et al.</emphasis>
2006b
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" box="[635,816,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Vitt, L. J., Magnusson, W. E., Avila-Pires, T. C. S. &amp; Lima, A. P. (2008) Guia de Lagartos da Reserva Adolpho Ducke, Amazonia Central = Guide to the Lizards of Reserva Adolpho Ducke, Central Amazonia. Attema Design Editorial, Manaus, 176 pp." type="book" year="2008">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[687,746,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
); found also in perianthropic environments (
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" refString="Dixon, J. R. &amp; Soini, P. (1975) The reptiles of the upper Amazon Basin, Iquitos region, Peru. Part 1. Lizards and Amphisbaenians. Milwaukee Public Museum, Contributions in Biology and Geology, 4, 1 - 58." type="journal article" year="1975">
Dixon &amp; Soini 1975, and specimens from Belém, 
<collectingCountry box="[607,680,511,536]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Brazil</collectingCountry>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
